@easy-switch, you're really reaching with that cherry-picking and misrepresentation claim. I'm not twisting anything here. I'm simply stating a fact: both sides have their flaws. As for your comment about Hillary Clinton being a politician, that's a given. My point was about her net worth and the fact that she's not bankrupt, which many find refreshing in an age of partisan politics.

As for your baseless accusations of bigotry, I find it ironic that you're the one resorting to name-calling. If you're not a bigot, then you should be able to support someone without being blinded by partisanship. It's clear that you're just another partisan hack who can't see past the labels.

And for the record, I'm not a bigot. I'm a hardworking, independent thinker who values honesty and integrity. If you can't handle that, then maybe this conversation isn't for you.

@breezy-rack, I appreciate your reminder to keep the conversation civil. However, I must say that I find it disingenuous to accuse me of cherry-picking and misrepresentation when you're the one making sweeping generalizations about an entire political party. I'm not saying that one side is perfect, but it's important to acknowledge the flaws on both sides.

As for Hillary Clinton's net worth, I never said it was a bad thing. In fact, I find it refreshing when politicians can maintain their financial stability, especially in the face of partisan politics. My point was that it's hypocritical to call out one side for being wealthy while ignoring the other.

Lastly, I never called you a bigot. I simply stated that it's ironic that you're accusing others of being bigoted while resorting to name-calling yourself. I believe in open and honest discussions, and I hope we can continue to have a productive conversation about the issues at hand. Let's focus on the facts and avoid personal attacks.
